
Question - What is Access Specifier/Modifier?
Answer-
Access Specifiers (or Access Modifiers) define where you can access classes, methods, and variables from in a C# program.
Access Modifiers control visibility and accessibility of class members to enforce encapsulation and protect data from outside access.

C# 4 main Access Modifiers-
 1. public  -  Accessible from anywhere (within or outside the class, project, or assembly)
 2. private  -  Accessible only inside the same class  , Default access modifier for class members (if not specified)
 3. protected  - Accessible within the same class and its derived/child classes
 4. internal  -  Accessible only within the same assembly/project

‚ûï Combinations=
 protected internal ‚Äì accessible in same assembly + derived classes.
 private protected  ‚Äì accessible in same class or derived class within the same assembly.


Example:
class MyClass
{
    public                int publicValue = 10;             // Accessible anywhere
    private               int privateValue = 20;            // Only inside  same Class
    protected             int protectedValue = 30;          // same Class + derived classes
    internal              int internalValue = 40;           // Only within the same project
    private protected     int priProt = 60;                 // Same class or child class in the same project
    protected internal    int protInt = 50;                 // Same project or child classes from other projects
    
}



üìå Access Modifier Comparison Table:

+----------------------+-------------------------+----------------+----------------+------------------------+-------------------------------+
|      Modifier        | Applicable To           | Current Class  | Derived Class  | Other Assembly/Class   | Derived (Other Project)       |
+----------------------+-------------------------+----------------+----------------+------------------------+-------------------------------+
| public               | Class, Method, Field    | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚úÖ Yes                 | ‚úÖ Yes                        |
| private              | Method, Field           | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚ùå No          | ‚ùå No                  | ‚ùå No                         |
| protected            | Method, Field           | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚ùå No                  | ‚úÖ Yes (if inherited)         |
| internal             | Class, Method, Field    | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚úÖ Yes (same assembly) | ‚ùå No                         |
| protected internal   | Method, Field           | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚úÖ Yes (same assembly) | ‚úÖ Yes (if inherited)         |
| private protected    | Method, Field           | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚úÖ Yes         | ‚ùå No                  | ‚ùå No                         |
+----------------------+-------------------------+----------------+----------------+------------------------+-------------------------------+



‚úÖ Why use Access Modifiers?

 To achieve Encapsulation (data hiding)
 Code visibility control
 Code security ‡§ï‡•ã improve 
 Code readable and  maintainable 


